item.title: Why New Moms Are Dying By Suicide
item.description: In January, at a pediatrician appointment for my then six-month-old daughter, I was handed an iPad-like device and asked to respond on a scale of 1 to 10 to prompts such as: 'In the past seven days, I have been able to laugh and see the funny side of things,' and 'I have been anxious or worried for no good reason.' The questionnaire is part of the Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale (EPDS), which is used to detect postpartum depression among mothers globally.
